Cell.Text: [S] So. You have made your way here, to me. No easy task for a joor... mortal. Even for one of Dovah Sos. Dragonblood. | What would you ask of me?
G|Not until introductions are complete. Zin. Heyv. Test your Thu'um against mine, Dovahkiin!
S|Drem Yol Lok. Greetings, wunduniik. I am Paarthurnax. | Who are you? What brings you to my strunmah... my mountain?
You are bold, wunduniik. You dare enter a Dovah's home without permission.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarIntroTopic

Cell.Text: [S] I am as my father Akatosh made me. As are you... Dovahkiin.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarIntroA1: I wasn't expecting you to be a dragon.

Cell.Text: [S] They see me as master. Wuth. Onik. Old and wise. It is true I am old...

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarIntroA2: You're the master of the Greybeards?

Cell.Text: [S] Yes. Vahzah. You speak true, Dovahkiin. Forgive me. | It has been long since I held tinvaak with a stranger. I gave in to the temptation to prolong our speech.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarIntroA3: I think you already know who I am.

Cell.Text: [S] G|Drem. Patience. There are formalities which must be observed, at the first meeting of two of the dov.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarIntroB1: I need to learn the Dragonrend Shout. Can you teach me?

Cell.Text: Evenaar bahlok. There are many hungers it is better to deny than to feed. | Dreh ni nahkip. Discipline against the lesser aids in qahnaar... denial of the greater.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarIntroA3A1: Why live alone on a mountain if you love conversation?

Cell.Text: <<Shared>> Tell me. Why do you come here, volaan? Why do you intrude on my meditation?

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarIntroB0

Cell.Text: True. But few now remember that this was the very spot where Alduin was defeated by the ancient Tongues. | Vahrukt unslaad... perhaps none but me now remember how he was defeated.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarB1: No. Dragons like mountains, right?

Cell.Text: This is the most sacred mountain in Skyrim. Zok revak strunmah. The great mountain of the world. | Here the ancient Tongues, the first mortal masters of the Voice, brought Alduin to battle and defeated him.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarB2: I never thought about it.

Cell.Text: Drem. Patience. I am answering, in my way.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarB3: You said you were going to answer my question.

Cell.Text: Yes and no. Viik nuz ni kron. Alduin was not truly defeated, either. If he was, you would not be here today, seeking to... defeat him. | The Nords of those days used the Dragonrend Shout to cripple Alduin. But this was not enough. Ok mulaag unslaad. | It was the Kel - the Elder Scroll. They used it to... cast him adrift on the currents of Time.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarC1: Using the Dragonrend Shout, right?

Cell.Text: [S] Tiid krent. Time was... shattered here because of what the ancient Nords did to Alduin. | If you brought that Kel, that Elder Scroll back here... to the Tiid-Ahraan, the Time-Wound... | With the Elder Scroll that was used to break Time, you may be able to... cast yourself back. To the other end of the break. | You could learn Dragonrend from those who created it.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarD1: How does any of this help me?

Cell.Text: Krosis. No. I know little of what has passed below in the long years I have lived here. | You are likely better informed than I.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarFindElderScrollTopic: Do you know where I can find an Elder Scroll?

Cell.Text: The Lorekeeper at the College of Winterhold might know.
[S] <<Shared>> Trust your instincts, Dovahkiin. Your blood will show you the way.
[S] <<Shared>> Trust your instincts, Dovahkiin. Your blood will show you the way.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarFindElderScrollA1: Hmm. Esbern or Arngeir might have some idea.

Cell.Text: Do you know why I live here, at the peak of the Monahven - what you name Throat of the World?
You have not answered my question. Why do you need to learn this Thu'um?
Can you teach me the Dragonrend Shout?
Ah. I have expected you. Prodah. | You would not come all this way for tinvaak with an old dovah. No. You seek your weapon against Alduin.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3Topic: I need to learn the Dragonrend Shout.

Cell.Text: S|Nid. If you wish me to answer your question, you must answer mine.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3A1: That's none of your business.

Cell.Text: Yes. Alduin... zeymah. The elder brother. Gifted, grasping and troublesome as is so often the case with firstborn. | But why? Why must you stop Alduin?

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3A2: I need to stop Alduin.

Cell.Text: True... But qostiid - prophecy - tells what may be, not what should be. | Qostiid sahlo aak. Just because you can do a thing, does not always mean you should. | Do you have no better reason for acting than destiny? Are you nothing but a plaything of dez... of fate?

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3B1: The prophecy says that only the Dragonborn can stop him.

Cell.Text: Pruzah. As good a reason as any. There are many who feel as you do, although not all. | Some would say that all things must end, so that the next can come to pass. | Perhaps this world is simply the Egg of the next kalpa? Lein vokiin? Would you stop the next world from being born?

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3A3: I like this world. I don't want it to end.

Cell.Text: Hahaha! You have much to learn of the dov, then. | There is nothing else but philosophy to a dovah. It is no accident that we do battle with our Thu'um, our Voices. | There is no distinction between debate and combat to a dragon. Tinvaak los grah. For us it is one and the same.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3C1: I didn't come here to debate philosophy with you.

Cell.Text: [S] Paaz. A fair answer. | Ro fus... maybe you only balance the forces that work to quicken the end of this world. | Even we who ride the currents of Time cannot see past Time's end. Wuldsetiid los tahrodiis. | Those who try to hasten the end, may delay it. Those who work to delay the end, may bring it closer.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3A3A1: The next world will have to take care of itself.

Cell.Text: If you can see your destiny clearly, your sight is clearer than mine. | Dahmaan - remember, Alduin also follows his destiny, as he sees it. | But, I bow before your certainty. In a way I envy you. The curse of much knowledge is often indecision.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3B1A1: What better reason to act than to fulfill my destiny?

Cell.Text: [S] And so, perhaps, your destiny will be fulfilled. Who can say? | Dez motmahus. Even to the dov, who ride the currents of Time, destiny is elusive. | Alduin believes that he will prevail, with good reason. Rok mul. | And he is no fool. Ni mey, rinik gut nol. Far from it. He began as the wisest and most far-seeing of us all.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3B1A2: I don't believe in destiny. But I will stop Alduin.

Cell.Text: [S] Drem. All in good time. First, a question for you. Why do you want to learn this Thu'um?

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3A: How can I learn it, then?

Cell.Text: [S] But you have indulged my weakness for speech long enough. Krosis. Now I will answer your question.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3D1

Cell.Text: Krosis. Sorrowfully, no. It cannot be known to me.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3Intro1: Do you know Dragonrend or not?

Cell.Text: <<Shared>> Your kind - joorre - mortals - created it as a weapon against the dov... the dragons. | Our hadrimme, our minds cannot even... comprehend its concepts.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3IntroCont: You don't know it?

Cell.Text: Hmm. Yes. They are very protective of me. Bahlaan fahdonne. | But I do not know the Thu'um you seek. Krosis. It cannot be known to me.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3Intro2: The Greybeards didn't want me to come at all.

Cell.Text: Alduin komeyt tiid. What else would you seek? Alduin and Dovahkiin return together. | But, I do not know the Thu'um you seek. Krosis. It cannot be known to me.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarDragonrend3Intro3: How did you know I came for Dragonrend?

Cell.Text: Hmm. How to explain in your tongue? The dov have words for such things that joorre do not. | It is an... artifact from outside time. It does not exist, but it has always existed. Rah wahlaan. They are...hmm... fragments of creation. | The Kelle... Elder Scrolls, as you name them, they have often been used for prophecy. Yes, your prophecy comes from an Elder Scroll. | But this is only a small part of their power. Zofaas suleyk.

Node.Caption: MQ204PaarC1A1: An Elder Scroll? What's that?

Cell.Text: [S] Not intentionally. Some hoped he would be gone forever, forever lost. Meyye. | I knew better. Tiid bo amativ. Time flows ever onward. One day he would surface. | Which is why I have lived here. For thousands of mortal years I have waited. I knew where he would emerge but not when.

Node.Caption: MMQ204PaarC1A2: Are you saying the ancient Nords sent Alduin forward in time?

Cell.Text: G|You have it. The Kel - the Elder Scroll. Tiid kreh... qalos. Time shudders at its touch. | There is no question. You are doom-driven. Kogaan Akatosh. The very bones of the earth are at your disposal. | Go then. Fulfill your destiny. Take the Scroll to the Time-Wound. | Do not delay. Alduin will be coming. He can not miss the signs.
G|Do not delay. Alduin must feel the tremors in Time by the Scroll's presence here. He will know what it means.

Node.Caption: MQ206PaarthurnaxBlockingTopic: I have the Elder Scroll.
